'''Huncovce''' ({{IPA-sk|ˈɦuntsɔʊ̯tsɛ}}; {{lang-hu|'''Hunfalva''', til 1902: '''Hunfalu'''}}, {{lang-de|'''Hunsdorf''', Hunszdorf, Hundsdorf in der Zips, Hunzdorf, Hunesdorf}},<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portal.gov.sk/Portal/sk/Default.aspx?CatID=109&cityID=523526 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809054455/https://portal.gov.sk/Portal/sk/Default.aspx?CatID=109&cityID=523526 |archivedate=2011-08-09 |df= }}</ref> {{lang-yi|'''אונסדאָרףֿ'''}} '''''Unsdorf''''', {{lang-he|אונסדורף}}, {{lang-la|Villa Canis, Hunisvilla}}) is a [[village]] and [[municipality]] in [[Kežmarok District]] in the [[Prešov Region]] of north [[Slovakia]].

== Geography ==
The [[municipality]] lies at an [[altitude]] of 639 metres and covers an [[area]] of 13.262&nbsp;km².
It has a [[population]] of about 2400 people.

== People ==
* [[David Friesenhausen]] (1750, [[Friesenhausen]] - 1828, Gyulafehérvár/Alba Iulia), a Jewish Bavarian-Hungarian Talmudist, scientist, mathematician, Hebrew-language writer; lived here<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=421&letter=F [[Jewish Encyclopedia]]], accessed 27 February 2014.</ref>
* [[Solomon Winter]] ({{lang-hu|Winter Salamon}}; 1778, ?, in the Szepes - ), Jewish Hungarian philanthropist; lived and died here

