[[File:Gallen-Kallela Joukahainen's revenge.jpg|thumb|Joukahainen preparing to shoot [[Väinämöinen]]]]
'''Joukahainen''' ({{IPA-fi|ˈjoukɑhɑinen}}) is a character in the [[Kalevala]], the [[Finland|Finnish]] [[epic poetry|epic poem]] of fifty parts. He is the rival of the main character, [[Väinämöinen]]. After losing a singing contest, he pledges his sister [[Aino (mythology)|Aino]] to Väinämöinen, but she drowns herself rather than marry him. Joukahainen, still envious of Väinämöinen, then shoots the stag of his rival from under him, plunging him into the waters of [[Pohjola]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Kalevala: the Finnish national epic - thisisFINLAND|url = http://finland.fi/arts-culture/kalevala-the-finnish-national-epic/|website = thisisFINLAND|accessdate = 2015-11-22|language = en-US}}</ref>

In the original translation into [[English language|English]] (by [[John Martin Crawford (scholar)|John Martin Crawford]] (1888)) this character's name was [[Anglicised]] as Youkahainen.

